, '26', '5', '393', '405', '10.1111/j.1467-8667.2010.00692.x', '13', 'Computer Science, Interdisciplinary Applications; Construction &$$Building Technology; Engineering, Civil; Transportation Science &$$Technology', 'Science Citation Index Expanded (SCI-EXPANDED)', 'Computer Science; Construction & Building Technology; Engineering;$$Transportation', '759CR', 'WOS:000290218500006', '2023-11-13', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Raphael, Benny/F-5795-2018', 'DIRECT STOCHASTIC ALGORITHM; LIGHT SHELF PERFORMANCE; GENETIC ALGORITHM;$$COST OPTIMIZATION; VISUAL COMFORT', 'Singapore Ministry of Education; Office of Research (ORE), NUS$$[R-296-000-102-112]', 'This research is supported by the Singapore Ministry of Education\'s AcRF$$Tier 1 funding and the Office of Research (ORE), NUS, through the grant$$R-296-000-102-112. The author wishes to thank his collaborators in this$$research work, Prof. Tham Kwok Wai and Prof. Chandra Sekhar for fruitful$$discussions. Comments by anonymous reviewers have been extremely useful$$in revising the article.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL);
INSERT INTO `t_sheet` VALUES (101, NULL, 'J', 'Xiong, T$$Zhang, MP$$Shu, CW$$Wong, SC$$Zhang, P', 'Xiong, Tao$$Zhang, Mengping$$Shu, Chi-Wang$$Wong, S. C.$$Zhang, Peng', 'High-Order Computational Scheme for a Dynamic Continuum Model for$$Bi-Directional Pedestrian Flows', 'COMPUTER-AIDED CIVIL AND INFRASTRUCTURE ENGINEERING', 'English', 'Article', 'In this article, we present a high-order weighted essentially non-oscillatory (WENO) scheme, coupled with a high-order fast sweeping method, for solving a dynamic continuum model for bi-directional pedestrian flows. We first review the dynamic continuum model for bi-directional pedestrian flows. This model is composed of a coupled system of a conservation law and an Eikonal equation. Then we present the first-order Lax-Friedrichs difference scheme with first-order Euler forward time discretization, the third-order WENO scheme with third-order total variation diminishing (TVD) Runge-Kutta time discretization, and the fast sweeping method, and demonstrate how to apply them to the model under study. We present a comparison of the numerical results of the model from the first-order and high-order methods, and conclude that the high-order method is more efficient than the first-order one, and they both converge to the same solution of the physical model.', '[Xiong, Tao; Zhang, Mengping] Univ Sci & Technol China, Dept Math, Hefei 230026, Anhui, Peoples R China.$$[Shu, Chi-Wang] Brown Univ, Div Appl Math, Providence, RI 02912 USA.$$[Wong, S. C.] Univ Hong Kong, Dept Civil Engn, Hong Kong, Hong Kong, Peoples R China.$$[Zhang, Peng] Shanghai Univ, Shanghai Inst Appl Math & Mech, Shanghai 200072, Peoples R China.', 'Chinese Academy of Sciences; University of Science & Technology of$$China, CAS; Brown University; University of Hong Kong; Shanghai$$University', 'Wong, SC (corresponding author), Univ Hong Kong, Dept Civil Engn, Hong Kong, Hong Kong, Peoples R China.', 'hhecwsc@hkucc.hku.hk', 'ZHANG, Peng/0000-0001-6953-800X; Shu, Chi-W