INSERT INTO `t_sheet` VALUES (116, NULL, 'J', 'Alshibli, KA$$Al-Hamdan, MZ', 'Alshibli, KA$$Al-Hamdan, MZ', 'Estimating volume change of triaxial soil specimens from planar images', 'COMPUTER-AIDED CIVIL AND INFRASTRUCTURE ENGINEERING', 'English', 'Article', 'A series of conventional triaxial experiments were conducted on sand specimens aboard the Space Shuttle during the NASA STS-79 mission. A 360 degrees video coverage to monitor the specimen deformations was recorded during the experiments. Post-flight analyses included retrieving the video images for fin-ther analysis. Analysis tools were developed to correct distortion in specimen images due to using wide-angle lenses employing quadratic polynomial functions implemented in a computer code. Planar projections of specimen video images were used along with the x-ray computed tomography images to reconstruct three-dimensional (3D) renderings of triaxial sand specimens at different axial strain levels. Volumetric change of the specimens was accurately calculated and compared to measurements recorded during the Shuttle flight. 3D renderings that show the progress of specimen deformations were also developed and displayed. Such results are valuable for documenting trite 3D recordings of soils instability phenomena tested using standard triaxial compression procedures and for applications related to educational demonstrations of conventional testing of soils.', 'Louisiana State Univ So Univ, Dept Civil & Environm Engn, CEBA 3507, Baton Rouge, LA 70803 USA.$$Univ Alabama, Dept Civil & Environm Engn, Huntsville, AL 35899 USA.', 'Louisiana State University System; Louisiana State University;$$University of Alabama System; University of Alabama Huntsville', 'Alshibli, KA (corresponding author), Louisiana State Univ So Univ, Dept Civil & Environm Engn, CEBA 3507, Baton Rouge, LA 70803 USA.', 'alshibli@lsu.edu', NULL, 'Alshibli KA, 2000, GEOTECH TEST J, V23, P274$$Alshibli KA, 1996, P SOC PHOTO-OPT INS, V2809, P303, DOI 10.1