20124G035]; China Postdoctoral Science$$Foundation [2016M592696]; Ri-Xin Talents Project of Beijing University$$of Technology [2017-RX(1)-16]', 'The authors would like to acknowledge staffs at Waylink, Dr. Shu Yang at$$the University of Arkansas, and Dr. Shaofan Wang at Beijing University$$of Technology, who assisted in field and lab data collection, system$$calibration, and data processing. In addition, the authors appreciate$$the financial support for this study provided by the National Social$$Science Foundation of China (Youth Program, Grant No. 16CGL001),$$National Natural Science Foundation of China (No. 51608019, 51478398,$$and U1534203), Beijing Excellent Talent Program (No. 2015000020124G035),$$China Postdoctoral Science Foundation Funded Project (No. 2016M592696),$$and the Ri-Xin Talents Project of Beijing University of Technology$$(2017-RX(1)-16). Last but not least, the authors would like to thank the$$Editor and the anonymous reviewers for their constructive comments and$$valuable suggestions to improve the quality of the article.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL);
INSERT INTO `t_sheet` VALUES (317, NULL, 'J', 'Thöns, S', 'Thoens, Sebastian', 'On the Value of Monitoring Information for the Structural Integrity and$$Risk Management', 'COMPUTER-AIDED CIVIL AND INFRASTRUCTURE ENGINEERING', 'English', 'Article', 'This article introduces an approach and framework for the quantification of the value of structural health monitoring (SHM) in the context of the structural risk and integrity management for systems. The quantification of the value of SHM builds upon the Bayesian decision and utility theory, which facilitates the assessment of the value of information associated with SHM. The principal approach for the quantification of the value of SHM is formulated by modeling the fundamental decision of performing SHM or not in conjunction with their expected utilities. The expected utilities are calculated accounting for the probabilistic performance of a system in conjunction with the associated structural integrity and risk management actions throughout the life cycle, the associated benefits, structural risks, and costs and when performing SHM, the SHM information, their probabilistic outcomes, and costs. The calculation of the expected utilities necessitates a comprehensive and rigorous modeling, which is introduced close to the original formulations and for which analysis characteristics and simplifications are described and derived. The framework provides the basis for the optimization of the structural risk and integrity management based on utility gains including or excluding SHM and inspection information. Studies of fatigue deteriorating structural systems and their characteristics (1) provide decision support for the performance of SHM, (2) explicate the influence of the structural component and system characteristics on the value of SHM, and (3) demonstrate how an integral optimization of SHM and inspection strategies for an efficient structural risk and integrity management can be performed.', '[Thoens, Sebastian] Tech Univ Denmark, Dept Civil Engn, Lyngby, Denmark.$$[Thoens, Sebastian] BAM Fed Inst Mat Res & Testing, Dept Safety Struct 7, Berlin, Germany.', 'Technical University of Denmark; Federal Institute for Materials$$Research & Testing', 'Thöns, S (corresponding author), Tech Univ Denmark, Dept Civil Engn, Lyngby, Denmark.; Thöns, S (corresponding author), BAM Fed Inst Mat Res & Testing, Dept Safety Struct 7, Berlin, Germany.', 'sebt@byg.dtu.dk', 'Thons, Sebastian/0000-0002-7714-3312', '[Anonymous], 2004, THESIS$$[Anonymous], 2015, ISO23942015$$[Anonymous], 2006, PROB MOD COD$$Au SK, 2001, PROBABILIST ENG MECH, V16, P263, DOI 10.1016/S0266-8920(01)00019-4$$Baker JW, 2008, STRUCT SAF, V30, P253, DOI 10.1016/j.strusafe.2006.11.004$$British Standards Institution, 2005, 7910 BS$$Brownjohn JMW, 2007, PHILOS T R SOC A, V365, P589, DOI 10.1098/rsta.2006.1925$$Cha YJ, 2015, COMPUT-AIDED CIV INF, V30, P347, DOI 10.1111/mice.12122$$Daniels HE, 1945, PROC R SOC LON SER-A, V183, P0405$$Döhler M, 2013, MECH SYST SIGNAL PR, V39, P426, DOI 10.1016/j.ymssp.2012.12.011$$Faber MH, 2014, SAFETY, RELIABILITY AND RISK ANALYSIS: BEYOND THE HORIZON, P2535$$Faber MH, 1997, SOLID MECH APPL, V56, P377$$Farrar C.R., 2013, STRUCTURAL HLTH MONI, DOI DOI 10.1002/9781118443118$$Folso R, 2002, MAR STRUCT, V15, P627, DOI 10.1016/S0951-8339(01)00031-4$$Frangopol DM, 2008, ENG STRUCT, V30, P3644, DOI 10.1016/j.engstruct.2008.06.010$$GOLLWITZER S, 1990, STRUCT SAF, V7, P229, DOI 10.1016/0167-4730(90)90072-W$$Goulet JA, 2015, STRUCT SAF, V52, P1, DOI 10.1016/j.strusafe.2014.08.001$$Huang QD, 2012, STRUCT SAF, V38, P11, DOI 10.1016/j.strusafe.2012.01.004$$Konakli Katerina, 2014, Vulnerability, Uncertainty, and Risk. Quantification, Mitigation, and Management. Second International Conference on Vulnerability and Risk Analysis and Management (ICVRAM) and the Sixth International Symposium on Uncertainty Modeling and Analysis (ISUMA). Proceedings, P1605$$Lee YJ, 2011, J ENG MECH, V137, P807, DOI 10.1061/(ASCE)EM.1943