INSERT INTO `t_sheet` VALUES (353, NULL, 'J', 'Li, T$$Wu, T', 'Li, Tao$$Wu, Teng', 'Modeling nonlinear flutter behavior of long-span bridges using$$knowledge-enhanced long short-term memory network', 'COMPUTER-AIDED CIVIL AND INFRASTRUCTURE ENGINEERING', 'English', 'Article', 'The nonlinear characteristics of bridge aerodynamics preclude a closed-form solution of limit-cycle oscillation (LCO) amplitude and frequency in the post-flutter stage. To address this issue, a long short-term memory (LSTM) network is utilized as the reduced-order modeling of nonlinear aeroelastic forces on the bridge deck section, and it is repeatedly employed to generate force inputs at spanwise nodes of a three-dimensional (3D) finite element model (FEM) of the long-span bridge (using spatial beam elements). All LSTM networks are dynamically coupled through FEM, and the 3D nonlinear flutter response is accordingly obtained. To improve the simulation accuracy and reduce the required training data of the standard LSTM network, both general knowledge (motivated by the gating mechanism and mathematical models for information processing) and domain knowledge (resulting from the basic understanding of bridge aerodynamics) are leveraged to, respectively, customize the LSTM cell and network architecture. In addition, a fast-training algorithm effectively combining the linear convergence of stochastic gradient descent and superlinear convergence of modified Broyden-Fletcher-Goldfarb-Shanno is developed to improve the training efficiency of the obtained knowledge-enhanced LSTM network. To further advance the computational efficiency of the coupled LSTM-FEM nonlinear flutter analysis, the convolution-based numerical integration is adopted in the finite element modeling of long-span bridge dynamics. A case study of a long-span suspension bridge under strong winds demonstrates the proposed 3D nonlinear flutter analysis presents high simulation efficiency and accuracy and can be utilized to effectively obtain the nonlinear LCO characteristics in a wide range of post-flutter wind speeds.', '[Li, Tao] East China Jiaotong Univ, Sch Civil Engn & Architecture, Nanchang, Peoples R China.$$[Wu, Teng] SUNY Buffalo, Dept Civil Struct & Environm Engn, Buffalo, NY 14260 USA.', 'East China Jiaotong University; State University of New York (SUNY)$$System; State University of New York (SUNY) Buffalo', 'Wu, T (corresponding author), SUNY Buffalo, Dept Civil Struct & Environm Engn, Buffalo, NY 14260 USA.', 'tengwu@buffalo.edu', NULL, 'ADELI H, 1994, APPL MATH COMPUT, V62, P81, DOI 10.1016/0096-3003(94)90134-1$$Alam KMR, 2020, NEURAL COMPUT APPL, V32, P8675, DOI 10.1007/s00521-019-04359-7$$[Anonymous], 2016, ADV MODELING SIMULAT$$ASCE, 2019, PREST PERF BAS WIND$$Atkinson KE, 2008, INTRO NUMERICAL ANAL$$Broyden C. G., 1970, Journal of the Institute of Mathematics and Its Applications, V6, P222$$Dung CV, 2019, AUTOMAT CONSTR, V99, P52, DOI 10.1016/j.autcon.2018.11.028$$Carassale L, 2014, J ENG MECH, V140, DOI 10.1061/(ASCE)EM.1943-7889.0000737$$[陈兰平 Chen Lanping], 2007, [数学进展, Advances in Mathematics], V36, P81$$Chen SK, 2020, COMPUT-AIDED CIV INF, V35, P305, DOI 10.1111/mice.12495$$Chen XZ, 2003, J ENG MECH, V129, P885, DOI 10.1061/(ASCE)0733-9399(2003)129:8(885)$$Chun PJ, 2022, COMPUT-AIDED CIV INF, V37, P1387, DOI 10.1111/mice.12793$$Chun PJ, 2021, COMPUT-AIDED CIV INF, V36, P61, DOI 10.1111/mice.12564$$Clough R., 1995, DYNAMICS STRUCTURES$$Davenport A. G., 1962, J STRUCT DIV ASCE, V88, P233, DOI [10.4319/lo.2013.58.2.0489, DOI 10.4319/1O.2013.58.2.0489, DOI 10.1061/JSDEAG.0000773]$$De Risi R, 2022, COMPUT-AIDED CIV INF, V37, P470, DOI 10.1111/mice.12745$$Deng CY, 2020, ISCIENCE, V23, DOI 10.1016/j.isci.2020.101656$$Diana G, 2008, J WIND ENG IND AEROD, V96, P1871, DOI 10.1016/j.jweia.2008.02.052$$DIANA G, 1993, J WIND ENG IND AEROD, V48, P329, DOI 10.1016/0167-6105(93)90144-D$$Dowell EH, 2001, ANNU REV FLUID MECH, V33, P445, DOI 10.1146/annurev.fluid.33.1.445$$Ge R., 2015, C LEARN