 Index Expanded (SCI-EXPANDED)', 'Computer Science; Construction & Building Technology; Engineering;$$Transportation', 'DW5CH', 'WOS:000383659200001', '2023-11-13', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Soga, Kenichi/AAP-8416-2020', 'COST OPTIMIZATION; IDENTIFICATION; PROBABILITIES; MODEL', 'EPSRC Centre for Smart Infrastructure and Construction at Cambridge$$University (EPSRC) [EP/K000314/1]; Tsinghua-Cambridge-MIT Low-carbon$$University Alliance; China Ministry of Education Key Lab of Eco-Planning$$& Green Building at Tsinghua University; EPSRC [EP/K000314/1] Funding$$Source: UKRI; Engineering and Physical Sciences Research Council$$[EP/K000314/1] Funding Source: researchfish', 'The authors would like to acknowledge the helpful comments of Professor$$Richard De Neufville of MIT and Dr. William Fawcett and Dr. Martin$$Hughes of Cambridge Architectural Research on the initial draft of this$$article. The authors also wish to thank Professors Cinzia Talamo and$$Giancarlo Paganin of the Politecnico di Milano as well as Denis Garber,$$He Qi, and Yeonsook Heo of Cambridge University for their technical$$advice. All authors wish to acknowledge the funding support of the EPSRC$$Centre for Smart Infrastructure and Construction at Cambridge University$$(EPSRC reference EP/K000314/1). Ying Jin would also like to acknowledge$$the funding support received from the Tsinghua-Cambridge-MIT Low-carbon$$University Alliance and the China Ministry of Education Key Lab of$$Eco-Planning & Green Building at Tsinghua University. The usual$$disclaimers apply and the authors alone are responsible for any views$$expressed and any errors remaining.', NULL, 'hybrid, Green Published', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL);
INSERT INTO `t_sheet` VALUES (382, NULL, 'J', 'Castillo, E$$Grande, Z$$Moraga, P$$Sánchez-Vizcaíno, J', 'Castillo, Enrique$$Grande, Zacarias$$Moraga, Paola$$Sanchez-Vizcaino, Jesus', 'A Time Partitioning Technique for Railway Line Design and Timetable$$Optimization', 'COMPUTER-AIDED CIVIL AND INFRASTRUCTURE ENGINEERING', 'English', 'Article', 'Existing computer models used to optimize railway timetables lead to a high complexity when the number of analyzed services exceeds a given threshold. A time partitioning technique is proposed which allows line design and timetable optimization and a reduction in the complexity of the problem by considering small time windows of the same or different durations in which the timetables of a small (equal or not) number of running trains are optimized in sequence. Though the optimal solution is not expected to be attained with this method, the analyzed examples demonstrate that the resulting solution is close to the global optimum and practically satisfactory. This technique can be used at the planning and implementation stages. Examples of two real lines are analyzed to show the goodness of the proposed methods. One is the network Madrid-Sevilla-Toledo-Malaga-Valencia-Albacete with a dense traffic of 170 trains per day. The second is the Palencia-Santander line with 70 trains in which as an alternative to a double-track proposal with a cost of MEuro 3,200 an alternate double-single-track (ADST) solution, with a cost of MEuro 330 (one tenth) is proposed.', '[Castillo, Enrique] Royal Acad Engn, Madrid, Spain.$$[Castillo, Enrique; Grande, Zacarias; Moraga, Paola] Univ Cantabria, Dept Appl Math & Computat Sci, Santander, Spain.$$[Moraga, Paola] Pontificia Univ Catolica Valparaiso, Valparaiso, Chile.$$[Sanchez-Vizcaino, Jesus] Univ Castilla La Mancha, Dept Civil Engn, Ciudad Real, Castilla La Man, Spain.', 'Universidad de Cantabria; Pontificia Universidad Catolica de Valparaiso;$$Universidad de Castilla-La Mancha', 'Castillo, E (corre